    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1889-10-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1889-10-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="170" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d170">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Lincoln</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1889-10-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 29,
                            1889</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 107.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department is gratified to learn by your
                        No. 101 of the 16th instant that the Canadian Government has directed the
                        non-enforcement, for an indefinite period, of the act of 1886 as to shipping
                        seamen before “shipping masters,” so far as American vessels are concerned;
                        and you will take occasion so to inform Her Majesty’s Government.</p>
                <p>As regards the discrimination against American vessels at Halifax in the
                        matter of pilotage dues, the Department can not doubt that the expected
                        decision of the authorities will be favorable.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">James G. Blaine.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
